Title: The Cottage
Source: V4
Act: I

===

~ Silas and Fleur's life together. The incomplete training. The Book. Silas is taken. Her last words crack open the question Fleur has never been allowed to finish.

The cottage has become two people's life. Silas has taught Fleur the identification of herbs, the treatment of wounds, the patience of sitting with the sick. Fleur is capable — and restless in a way she can't name. Good at the work, but unable to fully believe the work is enough.

The town at the forest's edge tolerates Silas's medicines and quietly fears the women who provide them. Fleur moves between cottage and town as a figure on the margin of both. She has heard the Chosen One whispers her whole life — in travellers' stories, in soldiers' talk passing through, carved into the Alderman's garrison walls. She has asked Silas about it. Silas has redirected, gently, consistently, for years. The consistency itself is an answer of a kind. Fleur has noticed it and drawn her own conclusion: Silas knows more than she says, and what she won't say is the important part.

The Book of Demons lives in its chest. Fleur has known it was there for as long as she can remember. She has been told — clearly, repeatedly — that it is not for her. Silas's voice when she says this is not harsh. It is the voice of someone managing a specific danger, the way you manage a fire in a dry season: not with alarm, but with constant careful attention.

The Alderman's soldiers arrive. They are not passing through. They are hunting Order remnants — tightening a net that has been closing for months.

Silas is calm in the way of someone who has been half-expecting this for a decade. She presses the chest key into Fleur's hands. "Hide. Do good. Never touch the Book." She holds Fleur's face for a moment — and then says the thing she has been unable to say, said now because there is no time left: "You are what I should have been."

She walks out to meet the soldiers. Fleur watches from the trees.

Silas is taken to the capital. The Alderman burns her expecting it to finally break Kestrel's silence. It does not. What it does is clarify something in Kestrel that has been complicated for a decade.

Fleur does not know any of this. She is alone in the empty cottage with a key in her hand.
